{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Tanhai\" (Solitude)**[^1]\n\n> Solitude[^2]  \n>   \n> Are the stars sorrowful in the night?  \n> Are they not your companions![^3]  \n>   \n> This lofty, silent sky so deep,  \n> The slumbering earth, the world asleep.[^4]  \n>   \n> This moon, the desert, vale, and mountain-bar,  \n> All Nature is a wild rose garden, near and far.[^5]  \n>   \n> These lovely pearls, so bright they are,  \n> Are but your tears, become a star.[^6]  \n>   \n> What is this longing you cannot remit, O heart!  \n> For Nature is your kindred spirit, O heart![^7]\n\nThis short poem from Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* (The Call of the Marching Bell, 1924) reflects on solitude amid nature's companionship, addressing the heart's restless longing despite the stars, earth, and moon as kindred spirits.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 25 \"Tanhai\" ([translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/)).\n[^2]: [p-125bb6](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/#p-125bb6).\n[^3]: [p-e79836](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/#p-e79836).\n[^4]: [p-0ef4d8](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/#p-0ef4d8).\n[^5]: [p-471a1d](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/#p-471a1d).\n[^6]: [p-36f218](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/#p-36f218).\n[^7]: [p-8846ae](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25-tanhai/translation/#p-8846ae).",
